Given the somewhat arbitrary nature of our definition of price wars and collusion, we then tried alternative definitions of price wars and collusion. The duration of the two pricing behaviours are reported in Fig. 4, Fig. 5
. Awar1 represents the beginning of a price war when the price has decreased by 15% from the previous month and an end of the war when the monthly average price has gone up by 10% from the previous month (or when the accumulated increases reach 10% in the previous consecutive months11
). Awar2 alternatively defines a price war with the necessary decrease being measured as 25% and the increase being 10%. Similarly, we have two definitions for collusion corresponding to Awar1 and Awar2 respectively.
